The problem is `IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory. Instead, read the raw request body stream and write it directly to disk.

**Solution: Stream directly from `Request.Body`**

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Disable the default form size limits
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Ensure the request is multipart
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary.");

    var reader = new Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities.MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var disposition)
            && disposition.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize name
            var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

            await using var fileStream = new FileStream(
                savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write, FileShare.None,
                bufferSize: 81920, useAsync: true);

            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream);
        }

        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
}).DisableAntiforgery();

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

1. **`MultipartReader`** — reads multipart sections one at a time from the stream; never buffers the whole file.
2. **Kestrel `MaxRequestBodySize`** — raise it to 2 GB (default is ~28 MB).
3. **`DisableAntiforgery()`** — required in .NET 8 minimal APIs for form uploads without an antiforgery token.
4. **Don't bind `IFormFile`** — that triggers the buffering you want to avoid.
5. **If behind IIS/reverse proxy**, also set `maxAllowedContentLength` in `web.config`:
   ```xml
   <requestFiltering>
     <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="2147483648" />
   </requestFiltering>
   ```

This approach uses constant memory (~80 KB buffer) regardless of file size.
